The paper deals with dynamic algorithms for the Steiner tree problem, which involves maintaining a tree that spans a set of changing terminals in a graph. This problem is related to topics such as data structures (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), network optimization (cs.NE), and game theory (cs.GT). The use of dynamic distance oracles is a key component of the algorithms presented, which further supports the relevance to the cs.DS category.
